      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"adaptation_kind\":\"Restructure\",\"safety_tier\":\"Green\",\"nudge_patch\":null,\"restructure_plan\":{\"revised_weekly_targets\":[{\"week_number\":1,\"weekly_target_km\":46},{\"week_number\":2,\"weekly_target_km\":50},{\"week_number\":3,\"weekly_target_km\":55}],\"revised_current_week_workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":2,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":8,\"target_duration_minutes\":48,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":360,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":360,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":370,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start very gently, shake out any residual fatigue.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":38,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":360,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Steady conversational effort throughout. If legs still feel heavy, back off to 370–380 s/km without hesitation.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":375,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Gradually ease to a walk, light stretching afterward.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"5 minutes very easy jogging before settling into rhythm.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"5 minutes easy jog into a walk; roll out quads and calves if needed.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This run is purely about re-establishing aerobic rhythm. There is no pace pressure here — treat the Daniels-Gilbert easy zone as a ceiling, not a target. If you feel flat, run by feel and simply accumulate time on feet.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":4,\"workout_type\":\"Tempo\",\"title\":\"Controlled Tempo Effort\",\"target_distance_km\":10,\"target_duration_minutes\":50,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":360,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":280,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":360,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy jogging to open up the legs before threshold work.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":25,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":290,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Run at a comfortably hard effort — slightly relaxed from full threshold pace. If 290 s/km feels forced, drift to 295–300 s/km and stay smooth.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":360,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Long, easy cooldown to flush the legs gently.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"10 minutes easy before the tempo block. Include 3–4 light strides in the last 2 minutes.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"15 minutes easy jogging followed by walking and light mobility work.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This is a shortened, slightly dialled-back tempo to let you re-engage with threshold work without digging deeper into fatigue. The target is smooth, sustained effort — not a time trial. Use the Daniels-Gilbert threshold zone as your guide and prioritise feel over split.\",\"perceived_effort\":6},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Comfortable Long Run\",\"target_distance_km\":16,\"target_duration_minutes\":96,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":360,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":355,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":370,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start very gently and let your body settle into the effort.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":76,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":358,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Steady aerobic long run entirely within the Daniels-Gilbert easy zone. No surges, no pickups — just consistent, comfortable mileage.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":375,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Ease back to a comfortable walk; prioritise refuelling and hydration immediately after.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Begin the first 10 minutes at a noticeably relaxed pace, letting heart rate rise naturally.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 5 minutes, refuel and hydrate, gentle stretching. This is an important recovery window.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"The long run is rebuilt from a comfortable 16 km this week. The goal is to finish feeling like you could have run further — not to push the distance. Easy aerobic effort throughout. A strong finish here sets up the progression over the next two weeks.\",\"perceived_effort\":5}],\"forward_path\":\"From a revised 46 km base this week, the plan returns to progression at roughly 9–10% per week: Week 2 targets 50 km with the interval session reinstated at a manageable volume (4 of 6 reps), and Week 3 builds to 55 km with the long run extending back toward 20 km. If Week 1 goes smoothly — legs feeling responsive, tempo effort holding well — Week 2 can reintroduce intervals at full rep count. The original 60/64/68 km meso structure becomes the template for a slightly shifted four-week block, keeping your sub-3:15 goal well within reach.\"},\"net_load_delta\":-14,\"rationale\":\"Three sessions in a row signalled that your body needed a reset, not just a tweak — flat legs on the intervals, a tempo that required backing off pace, and a long run cut short are all pointing in the same direction: you were carrying more accumulated fatigue than the plan accounted for. That's useful information, not a setback.\\n\\nWhat the data shows is a consistent pattern of effort-to-output mismatch across different workout types, which typically reflects systemic fatigue rather than any single bad day. The right response is to step back, let the system absorb the stress you've already built, and re-engage with a lighter week.\\n\\nHere's what's changed for this week: Tuesday's easy run is trimmed to 8 km with no pace pressure at all. Thursday's tempo is shortened to 10 km with a slightly relaxed threshold target so you can reconnect with that effort without forcing it. Saturday's long run is rebuilt at a comfortable 16 km — finish feeling strong rather than scraped empty. The weekly total drops to around 46 km, which gives your legs genuine room to recover.\\n\\nThe path forward is straightforward: Week 2 steps back up to 50 km with intervals returning at a reduced rep count, and Week 3 moves to 55 km as the long run builds back toward 20 km. You might find that after one lighter week things feel noticeably fresher — that freshness is exactly what threshold and interval work needs to land properly. Your sub-3:15 goal has plenty of runway, and a well-absorbed week now is a better investment than grinding through fatigue.\",\"referral_category\":null}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
